BOS


The integration of digital devices and online tools has become essential in programming education. Through laptops, mobile devices, and coding platforms, students gain access to a vast range of resources that can enhance their learning experiences. The Unified Theory of Acceptance and Use of Technology (UTAUT) by Venkatesh et al. (2003) provides a theoretical basis for understanding how individuals adopt and use new technologies.

According to UTAUT, factors such as Performance Expectancy, Effort Expectancy, and Social Influence influence an individual’s Behavioral Intention to use technology, which subsequently predicts Use Behavior. This framework is widely used to study positive technology adoption.

However, recent studies (e.g., Pérez-Juárez et al., 2024; Hazelhurst et al., 2011) highlight that not all technology use leads to beneficial outcomes. Students may exhibit misaligned or non-academic use—commonly termed as “digital distraction”—which can reduce learning effectiveness and academic performance. Thus, while UTAUT assumes a positive relationship between Behavioral Intention and Use Behavior, these findings suggest that the quality of use may moderate this relationship.

This study therefore applies the UTAUT framework to explore students’ acceptance and use of digital tools in coding education, while incorporating a caveat: that excessive or non-academic use may lead to diminished coding performance.

Juarez-perez's study

Pérez-Juárez et al. (2023) found that among engineering students, higher reported digital distractions are significantly correlated with lower self-assessed lab performance. This suggests that even when students have access to technology and likely positive intention to use it, the quality of actual use matters—non-academic/distractive usage can degrade performance. Through their study, we can determine that the missalignment of the intended use of a device and the actual use of said device proves a potential caveat of misuse when implementing figital devices
